INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'3-2-1 Contact', N'3-2-1-contact', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Parallel to a famed television series, this publication explored science in everyday life, games, and puzzles from 1983 to 1985, with a brief return in 1989.}}The 3-2-1 Contact magazine was a publication that paralleled the television series. It featured content related to the scientific and educational themes of the show, including write-ups on the science of everyday life, games, and puzzles. The magazine also included a serialized mystery series that followed a group of young detectives, known as the Bloodhound Gang, who used science to solve mysteries.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In terms of the timeline, the magazine ran from 1983 to 1985, with a brief return in syndication in 1989. This coincided with the show’s original run, which spanned from 1980 to 1988.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- ANALOG Computing
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'ANALOG Computing', N'analog-computing', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Dedicated to Atari 8-bit computers, this 1980s and 1990s periodical offered programming advice, hardware reviews, and hands-on coding exercises. Its significant impact on the understanding and use of these computers continues to resonate today.}}*ANALOG Computing* magazine was a prominent periodical in the field of computer technology, particularly during the 1980s and 1990s. The magazine stood out as a comprehensive resource for those interested in the Atari 8-bit family of home computers, focusing not only on programming but also on general usage, hardware, and software reviews.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### History ###' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Founded in 1981 by Lee Pappas and John Ziegler, Analog Computing Magazine quickly positioned itself as a trusted voice in the rapidly growing field of personal computing. The magazine was first based in Worcester, Massachusetts, before moving to its later base in Chelmsford.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The name "Analog" was a nod to the analog synthesis capabilities of Atari 8-bit computers, showcasing the magazine’s dedication to this computer series. Analog Computing initially published six issues per year, but due to its success and the booming interest in Atari computers, it increased its frequency to monthly publication in the mid-1980s.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Content and Features ###' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Analog Computing was known for its broad range of content, which appealed to a variety of readers, from hobbyists and novice users to advanced programmers and computer science professionals. It offered in-depth software and hardware reviews, how-to guides, game walkthroughs, interviews with industry figures, and, most importantly, programming advice and tutorials.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine’s iconic features was its type-in programs, which allowed readers to manually input computer programs into their Atari systems. This was a common practice in the 1980s before software distribution became widespread, and it gave many young computer users their first taste of programming.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another standout feature of the magazine was its dedication to quality writing and comprehensive reviews. The contributors to Analog Computing were deeply involved in the computing scene, and their insight and expertise showed in their articles. This commitment to quality and insightfulness set the magazine apart from its competitors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'### Influence and Legacy ###' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Analog Computing had a significant impact on the popular understanding and use of the Atari 8-bit family of computers. The magazine played an instrumental role in educating its readers about programming and the potential of personal computers, inspiring many to delve deeper into the world of computing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine ceased publication in 1989, a casualty of the declining market for Atari 8-bit computers as the industry moved toward 16-bit systems like the Commodore Amiga and Atari ST. However, its legacy lives on. Many programmers and computer enthusiasts cite Analog Computing as a significant influence on their careers and personal interests.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite its ultimate demise, the magazine’s contributions to the Atari 8-bit community and the broader field of personal computing are still acknowledged and respected today. It remains a notable part of computer history, representing an era of innovation, discovery, and excitement about the possibilities of home computing.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 7ball
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'7ball', N'7ball', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Influential in the Christian music scene from the mid-1990s to early 2000s, this American bimonthly publication was known for its diverse coverage and inclusion of sampler CDs in each issue.}}**7ball Magazine** was an American bimonthly magazine that made significant contributions to the Christian music scene from the mid-1990s through the early 2000s. Known for its diverse coverage of both mainstream and independent Christian music, 7ball broadened the dialogue about faith-based music within the larger cultural conversation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Established in 1995, 7ball Magazine was the brainchild of Chris Well, a seasoned journalist with a passion for Christian music. The magazine was originally published by VoxCorp, based in Nashville, Tennessee, a city known for its thriving music scene. In 1999, the publication was acquired by the Cornerstone Publishing Group, which continued to produce the magazine until its final issue in 2004.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'7ball was known for its comprehensive music reviews, feature articles, artist interviews, and coverage of Christian music events. The magazine was not confined to one musical genre but instead embraced the diversity within the Christian music scene. It covered a broad range of genres, from rock, pop, and hip hop to worship, gospel, and contemporary Christian music.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine’s distinguishing features was the inclusion of a sampler CD in each issue. These CDs featured tracks from the artists profiled in the magazine, providing readers with a tangible extension of the publication’s content. This innovative approach served as a powerful promotional tool for both established artists and emerging talent within the Christian music scene.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another notable aspect of 7ball was its commitment to high-quality, professional journalism. The magazine’s writers and contributors were experienced professionals who approached their work with a discerning eye for detail, accuracy, and relevance.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'7ball Magazine played an instrumental role in bringing attention to the Christian music scene, fostering a broader appreciation for faith-based music and the artists who create it. During its run, the magazine profiled many influential artists and bands, including Jars of Clay, DC Talk, and Switchfoot, among others.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Although 7ball ceased publication in 2004, its influence on the Christian music industry can still be felt today. Its commitment to quality journalism, diverse content, and promotion of emerging talent set a standard for other publications in the field.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Many former readers and contributors recall 7ball as a significant influence in shaping their musical tastes and understanding of Christian music. Despite the magazine’s eventual discontinuation, its contributions to the Christian music industry are still acknowledged and respected today.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 7x7
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'7x7', N'7x7', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A critical influencer of San Francisco''s cultural landscape since 2001, this publication covers diverse aspects of lifestyle and features local businesses. Transitioned to digital in 2014, it continues to thrive.}}*7x7 Magazine* is a prominent lifestyle and culture publication based in San Francisco, California. The publication has held a critical role in chronicling and influencing the Bay Area''s cultural landscape since its inception in 2001. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## History' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*7x7* was established in 2001 by Tom Hartle and Heather Hartle, with the aim of catering to San Francisco’s vibrant and diverse cultural scene. The magazine’s title is a reference to the approximate land area of San Francisco, which is roughly seven by seven miles. Initially, the magazine was printed in a monthly format. However, in 2014, *7x7* transitioned to a digital-first platform, focusing primarily on their online content while continuing to produce special print editions.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*7x7 Magazine* offers a broad range of content focusing on various aspects of San Francisco lifestyle and culture. The publication covers topics such as food and drink, arts and culture, style and design, health and wellness, and travel. Additionally, *7x7* also publishes feature articles on the city''s most notable individuals and spotlights unique local businesses and startups.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'One of the magazine''s standout features is its “Best of the Bay Area” issue. This annual edition is a comprehensive guide to the finest offerings in the region, spanning categories such as dining, shopping, entertainment, and outdoor activities. It''s regarded as an essential resource for both locals and visitors.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another notable feature of *7x7* is its in-depth and engaging long-form features. These articles often delve into significant cultural, social, or historical aspects of the Bay Area, presenting readers with a comprehensive understanding of the region''s dynamic nature.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*7x7 Magazine* has played a crucial role in San Francisco''s cultural scene. Through its insightful coverage of local events, trends, and personalities, *7x7* has helped to shape the discourse around what defines the city and its inhabitants.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Despite the shift from print to digital, the magazine continues to thrive, maintaining its relevance in a city known for its technological innovation. The move to digital has allowed *7x7* to reach an even broader audience, further solidifying its place as an integral part of San Francisco''s cultural landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In summary, *7x7 Magazine* serves as a rich source of information and inspiration for its readers, and its contributions to the preservation and promotion of San Francisco''s cultural heritage continue to be highly valued.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- 032c
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'032c', N'032c', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription First published in 2001, this Berlin-based magazine covers contemporary culture, art, fashion, and politics. Known for its critical journalism and avant-garde design.}}*032c* is a Berlin-based, English-language biannual contemporary culture magazine that was first published in 2001. The publication was created by Joerg Koch, who continues to serve as its editor-in-chief. It is named after the Pantone designation for the color red, referencing the vibrant energy and creativity associated with the city of Berlin.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In its early years, *032c* was primarily focused on contemporary art, fashion, and politics. Over time, the magazine expanded its scope to become a platform for critical journalism and innovative visual culture, encompassing a broad range of topics from pop culture and fashion to architectural design and global politics.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*032c* is noted for its in-depth and meticulously researched articles, coupled with provocative and avant-garde visual design. The magazine presents a unique blend of high-end fashion editorials, comprehensive profiles of artists and designers, thought-provoking think pieces, and immersive reportage.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of *032c* features a thematic focus, but the magazine doesn''t limit itself to its chosen theme, rather, it uses the theme as a starting point from which to explore the myriad ways in which contemporary culture is intertwined and coalescing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine also distinguishes itself with its commitment to exploring the intersection of different fields and disciplines, such as the cross-pollination between art, fashion, design, and technology. This holistic approach sets *032c* apart from its contemporaries and contributes to its unique identity in the magazine landscape.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'In the world of contemporary culture magazines, *032c* has carved out a significant niche for itself. It''s recognized for its intellectual rigor and its willingness to push the boundaries of traditional magazine journalism, both in its content and its visual presentation.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'While the magazine maintains a firm foothold in its Berlin home base, its influence extends far beyond. Its comprehensive approach to covering global contemporary culture has made it a critical resource for readers interested in understanding the intricacies of today''s world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine’s influence is also apparent in its contribution to critical dialogue and creative expression in contemporary culture. Many notable figures in the realms of art, design, fashion, and beyond have been featured in *032c*, with the magazine often serving as a platform for emerging voices in these fields.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*032c*''s innovative and broad-ranging approach to contemporary culture continues to shape its identity as a publication that not only reflects the world around it but also actively participates in shaping that world.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- Acne Paper
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'Acne Paper', N'acne-paper', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription A Swedish fashion brand''s biannual culture magazine (2005-2014) focused on thematic deep-dives rather than trends. Known for its artistic and intellectually engaging content.}}Founded in 2005, *Acne Paper* is a biannual culture magazine and the brainchild of the Swedish fashion brand Acne Studios. The magazine was conceived by Acne''s Creative Director Jonny Johansson and Thomas Persson, the editor-in-chief and art director of the publication. *Acne Paper* focused on themes, rather than specific topics or trends, aiming to delve deep into a single concept with each issue, until its final issue in 2014.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'From its inception, *Acne Paper* distinguished itself from other fashion magazines by concentrating less on the seasonal nature of fashion, but more on the exploration of broader themes such as tradition, eroticism, education, and decadence, to name a few. The result was a publication that was both highly artistic and intellectually engaging.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Each issue of *Acne Paper* was curated around a central theme, which was investigated through a variety of lenses, including interviews, essays, photography, and artistic contributions. This thematic approach allowed the magazine to transcend the typical constraints of fashion publications and delve into a rich dialogue spanning history, culture, and society.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Moreover, *Acne Paper* was celebrated for its aesthetic presentation. It utilized an impressive format, with high-quality paper and printing techniques. The magazine''s striking design and attention to detail earned it a reputation as not only a publication but also a collector''s item.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*Acne Paper* has had a significant impact on the landscape of fashion and culture publications. Its thematic approach set it apart from its contemporaries and contributed to an ongoing dialogue about the interplay between fashion, culture, and society. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Its influence also extended to the artistic community, as it often featured collaborations with acclaimed photographers, artists, and thinkers. Notably, it was recognized for spotlighting both established and emerging talents, thus providing a platform for creative expression across various fields.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though *Acne Paper* ceased publication in 2014, its legacy continues to resonate. Its unique editorial approach and artistic presentation have left an enduring imprint on the field of fashion journalism. Its archival issues remain relevant, offering timeless explorations of their respective themes.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- The New York Times Magazine
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'The New York Times Magazine', N'the-new-york-times-magazine', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Launched in 1896, this Sunday newspaper supplement features in-depth analysis, profiles, essays, and critiques across various domains. Known for its iconic Crossword and "The Ethicist" column.}}*The New York Times Magazine* is a supplemental publication included with the Sunday edition of *The New York Times*. Launched in 1896, it''s one of the oldest magazine supplements for a newspaper in the United States. Its founding aim was to present in-depth and thoughtful explorations of current events, trends, and societal issues that went beyond the daily news coverage provided by *The New York Times*. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The New York Times Magazine* features a wide range of content, including long-form reportage, profiles, essays, and critiques. Topics covered span the spectrum of human interest, from politics, science, and technology to art, literature, and popular culture. The magazine’s commitment to thorough reporting, elegant prose, and nuanced analysis has distinguished it as a staple of Sunday morning reading for many.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'A hallmark of *The New York Times Magazine* is its “The Lives They Lived” issue, released annually at year’s end. This issue remembers notable figures who have passed away during the year, celebrating their lives and contributions through evocative writing and photography. ' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The New York Times Magazine* also notably hosts the "The New York Times Puzzles & Games" section, which includes the iconic *New York Times* Crossword, a cultural fixture since its introduction in 1942. The section, under the editorship of Will Shortz since 1993, has expanded to include a variety of other puzzles, such as KenKen and Spelling Bee.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Another significant feature is "The Ethicist," a weekly column where readers submit ethical dilemmas to be dissected and addressed. This feature, currently authored by Kwame Anthony Appiah, encourages readers to engage with the moral complexities of modern life.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*The New York Times Magazine* has had a significant impact on journalism and storytelling. Its feature articles have often sparked discussion and drawn attention to pressing societal issues. Furthermore, its dedication to the craft of long-form journalism has provided a platform for many award-winning pieces.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Over the years, the magazine has been a podium for numerous esteemed writers and journalists, including Elizabeth Kolbert, Taffy Brodesser-Akner, Nikole Hannah-Jones, and Ronen Bergman, among others. Notably, the 1619 Project, a landmark initiative examining the impact of slavery on American society, was first published in *The New York Times Magazine* under the leadership of Hannah-Jones.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s commitment to deep-dive reporting, innovative storytelling, and thought-provoking commentary continues to influence the landscape of contemporary journalism. Its dedication to these principles ensures that *The New York Times Magazine* remains a revered publication in the constantly evolving world of media.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

-- FRUiTS
INSERT Articles (Title, UrlSlug, SiteId, Culture)
VALUES ( N'FRUiTS', N'fruits', 1, 'en' );
INSERT ArticleRevisions (ArticleId, [Text], RevisionReason, CreatedByAspNetUserId)
VALUES (SCOPE_IDENTITY(), N'{{ShortDescription Founded in Tokyo in 1997, this street fashion magazine popularized Harajuku''s eclectic style. Its legacy endures, despite ending publication in 2017.}}*FRUiTS* was a renowned Tokyo-based street fashion magazine that captured and popularized the eclectic and vibrant street style of Harajuku, a district in Tokyo known for its fashion subcultures. The magazine was founded in 1997 by photographer Shoichi Aoki, who had previously established the avant-garde fashion magazine *STREET*.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Aoki was inspired to create *FRUiTS* after noticing the inventive, do-it-yourself spirit of young people in the Harajuku district. The magazine quickly became a cultural touchstone, with its monthly issues featuring candid street-style photographs of the eccentric and original outfits worn by individuals around Harajuku.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Content and Features' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS* was characterized by its distinctive snapshot aesthetic. Each issue was filled with photographs of individuals in their unique outfits, often accompanied by a brief description of the person’s clothing and accessories. The magazine did not feature articles or editorials; instead, it relied on the power of its images to tell a story about the dynamism and creativity of Harajuku’s fashion culture.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The publication celebrated individuality and self-expression, as showcased by the people featured in its pages. Many of these individuals were not professional models but ordinary people with extraordinary style, reflecting the magazine’s ethos of street fashion as an accessible and personal form of expression.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'The magazine''s focus on Harajuku''s street style had a significant influence on international fashion trends. It brought global attention to various Japanese fashion movements, including “Decora,” a style characterized by layered clothing and accessories, and “Lolita,” a fashion subculture inspired by Victorian and Rococo clothing.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'## Influence and Legacy' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'*FRUiTS* gained an international following and had a significant impact on global fashion trends. The magazine has been credited with introducing and popularizing Harajuku street style to a global audience, influencing designers and fashion enthusiasts around the world.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'After twenty years of documenting Harajuku''s ever-changing street fashion scene, *FRUiTS* published its final issue in February 2017. Aoki cited a “lack of fashionable kids” to photograph as the reason for the magazine’s closure. He noted that, in his view, street fashion had become more homogenized and less innovative in recent years.' + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + CHAR(13) + CHAR(10) + N'Though the magazine is no longer in publication, its legacy endures. *FRUiTS* remains a symbol of Harajuku’s unique fashion subcultures and a testament to the district’s influence on global fashion. The magazine’s archives offer a colorful and diverse record of two decades of Tokyo street fashion, making *FRUiTS* an important part of the history of fashion documentation.{{Categories Magazines}}', N'Article created.', '7240be61-df81-46f9-8152-6a48b96abc40');

